DESCRIPTION_E62: The property meets the criteria for HCM designation because it embodies the ''distinguishing characteristics of an architectural-type specimen, inherently valuable for a study of a period style or method of construction,'' as an example of textile block construction and design. This system was designed to provide a modular approach to on-site construction. It is also associated with the ''notable work of a master builder, designer, or architect,'' as a work by master architect Frank Lloyd Wright, and supervised by his son Lloyd Wright. The residence is one of four textile block homes he designed. Other architects who worked on the home through the 1960s include Rudolph Schindler, Robert Clark and John Lautner. The Period of Significance end date is listed as 1952, which is approximately when Schindler finished the guest apartments and furnishings for the home. The HCM nomination is unclear about when the contributions by Clark and Lautner were made.\nThe property meets Criterion C for National Register designation for similar reasons.

DESCRIPTION_E62: The property meets the criteria for HCM designation because it reflects 'the broad cultural, political, economic or social history of the nation, state, or community,' for its association with the Case Study House program (1945-1966), which profoundly influenced mid-twentieth century residential design. Sponsored by John Entenza's Arts & Architecture magazine, the Case Study Houses were experiments in residential architecture designed to help meet the demands of the postwar housing boom. Leading architects were commissioned to create model residences using inexpensive materials and innovative design. The property is a National Historic Landmark and meets Criterion A for National Register designation for similar reasons.

The property meets the criteria for HCM designation because it reflects +G+the broad cultural, political, economic or social history of the nation, state, or community,+G- as an intact reminder of a major landholding family in early Los Angeles. The Marquez and Reyes families were deeded Rancho Boca de Santa Monica by the governor of Mexico in 1839. The Marquez portion, where the cemetery lies, covered areas of the San Fernando Valley and Santa Monica, Pacific Palisades, and Topanga Canyons. The surrounding area is now a residential neighborhood, and the walled cemetery is protected by an easement. The Period of Significance ends in 1952, when the cemetery's last owner of record died. The property has since been maintained by descendants of the Marquez family.

DESCRIPTION_E62: SS Dominator, a freighter, ran ashore on the Palos Verdes Peninsula in the South Bay area of California in 1961 due to a navigational error while lost in fog. Its remains can still be seen today, and serves as a point of interest for hikers and kayakers.

DESCRIPTION_OF_LOCATION_E62: The nearest access point is the park along the cove to the south. A different trailhead down to the beach leading to the site begins about 2 miles north along the coast on Paseo Del Mar between Via Horcada and Via Almar in Palos Verdes Estates, California.

DESCRIPTION_E62: Now part of The Henry Ford museum, This house originally stood near the laboratory where Thomas Edison and his men toiled in Menlo Park, New Jersey. Widowed in 1877, 'Aunt Sally,' as Sarah was known, lived in Newark, and was sent for in 1878 by her distant relative, Thomas Edison, to run a place for his workers to eat and sleep. With little employment opportunities for women, Mrs. Jordan accepted the offer and opened the home as a boarding house that same year. Several of Edison's single employees lived here and would sleep two to three to a bed in the six rooms on the second floor. In fact, at the height of the laboratory's activities in 1880, sixteen boarders called this structure 'home.'

DESCRIPTION_OF_LOCATION_E62: The Sarah Jordan Boarding House was located near Thomas Edison's Menlo Park Laboratory in New Jersey before being moved to the Greenfield Village area of The Ford museum in Dearborn, Michigan.
